In TypeScript, you can use type guards to tell the type system that you know a value will only have one specific type, even though it could theoretically have multiple types. A type guard is a way to narrow down the type of a variable within a conditional block.

Here's an example to illustrate how you can use type guards:

```typescript
interface Animal {
    sound: string;
}

interface Dog extends Animal {
    bark: () => string;
}

interface Cat extends Animal {
    meow: () => string;
}

function createAnimalFactory<T extends Animal>(type: T): T {
    return {
        sound: "some sound",
        // Here, TypeScript knows `type` is of type `T` and can provide appropriate type checks
    };
}

// This is a type guard for `Dog`
function isDog(animal: Animal): animal is Dog {
    return (animal.bark !== undefined);
}

// This is a type guard for `Cat`
function isCat(animal: Animal): animal is Cat {
    return (animal.meow !== undefined);
}

const factory = createAnimalFactory<Dog>({
    sound: "bark",
    bark: () => "woof",
});

if (isDog(factory)) {
    // Here, TypeScript knows `factory` is of type `Dog`
    console.log(factory.bark()); // Type safety ensured
} else if (isCat(factory)) {
    // Here, TypeScript knows `factory` is of type `Cat`
    console.log(factory.meow()); // Type safety ensured
} else {
    console.log("Unknown animal type");
}
```

In this example:

1. `createAnimalFactory` is a function that returns an object of type `Animal`, but you know it will only be one specific type (`Dog` or `Cat`).
2. `isDog` and `isCat` are type guard functions that narrow down the type of `Animal` to `Dog` or `Cat`, respectively, within the conditional block.

By using these type guards, you can ensure that TypeScript understands the actual type of the value within the respective conditional blocks, providing better type safety and tooling support.

