```C++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <algorithm>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("example.txt"); // open file

    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cout << "Failed to open file" << std::endl;
        return 1; // return with error
    }

    std::string wordToFind;
    std::cout << "Enter the word to find: ";
    std::cin >> wordToFind;

    std::string line;
    int count = 0;

    while (std::getline(file, line)) { // read line by line
        std::transform(line.begin(), line.end(), line.begin(), ::tolower); // convert line to lower case
        std::string word;
        std::stringstream ss(line);

        while (ss >> word) {
            std::transform(word.begin(), word.end(), word.begin(), ::tolower); // convert word to lower case
            if (word == wordToFind) {
                ++count;
            }
        }
    }

    file.close(); // close file

    std::cout << "Word \"" << wordToFind << "\" found " << count << " times" << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program first opens a file called "example.txt". If the file cannot be opened, it prints an error message and returns with an error code.

The user then inputs the word they want to find in the file. All lines in the file are then read one by one. Each line is converted to lower case to ensure the word count is case insensitive. The line is then split into words, and each word is also converted to lower case. If any word matches the word the user is looking for, the count is increased.

After all the lines have been read, the program outputs the total count of the specified word and closes the file.

